{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A unit test over prompt-building logic could miss failures introduced where the classifier module wires prompt construction into the API client call. An integration test with a fake local API transport can inspect the actual outbound request assembled by the module and catch dropped, reordered, or partially omitted labels without needing a real external service.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a local fake API client/transport that records requests. Invoke classification with a sample document and assert the outbound request contains every configured taxonomy label exactly as the module sends them to the API.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is usually at the boundary between the external API response parser and the taxonomy validation logic. A pure unit test of the validator alone is weaker because it can miss schema-mapping or response-shape issues in the assembled module. An integration test with a stubbed API response is enough; no real network or model behavior is required.","test_description":"Run the classifier against a fake API client that returns a successful response containing an out-of-taxonomy label such as `medical`. Assert the module returns `unknown` to the caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"If the module truly delegates the decision to an external AI API, repeated-call stability depends on real model nondeterminism, provider defaults, and sampling behavior. A mocked client or canned response would trivially pass and would not catch the real failure mode of inconsistent labels across live calls. One real model step repeated multiple times is sufficient; no multi-step pipeline is involved.","test_description":"Call the real classification API through the module multiple times with the same fixed document under production-like settings, then assert the returned label remains the same across runs for that document.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Token consumption is often measured by the real provider or real tokenizer behavior exposed through the external API. In-process mocks can miss provider-side token accounting, hidden prompt wrappers, or SDK/request serialization overhead. A system test against the real API or a real token-accounting endpoint can catch budget overruns without requiring model-quality evaluation.","test_description":"Send a representative document through the module using the real API path and assert the reported prompt/request token usage for that call is less than or equal to the configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on retry timing and handling of a realistic rate-limit signal from the API boundary. A pure in-process mock can miss SDK-level retry interactions, backoff parsing, and wall-clock waiting behavior. A system test against a controllable HTTP test server or real subprocess-based API simulator is sufficient; it does not require a live model response.","test_description":"Point the module at a controllable test HTTP server that first returns a rate-limit response and then a valid classification response. Assert the module delays, retries automatically, and ultimately returns the successful label instead of surfacing the initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.74,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
